{
  "doc_id": "45515",
  "text": "2.3.4. Arousal measure. Pre-sleep arousal was evaluated with the Pre-sleep Arousal Scale (PSAS) [CITATION_1] . PSAS is a 16-item, self-reported questionnaire comprising both cognitive and somatic manifestations of arousal, with eight items in each subscale. Two subscale scores ranging from 8 to 40 were computed separately: Pre-sleep Arousal Scale Cognitive Arousal (PSAS-C) with sum items 1-8, and Pre-sleep Arousal Scale Somatic Arousal (PSAS-S) with sum items [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . When responding to the PSAS, subjects were asked to describe how intensely they generally experienced each component as they attempted to fall asleep in their own bedroom by selecting an appropriate rating of \"1: do not at all,\" \"2: slightly,\" \"3: moderately,\" \"4: a lot,\" or \"5: extremely,\" during the past week.",
